  abstract = {We present our current progress on the design and  analysis of path planning algorithms based on Rapidlyexploring Random Trees (RRTs). The basis for our  methods is the incremental construction of search trees  that attempt to rapidly and uniformly explore the state  space, offering benefits that are similar to those ob\- tained by other successful randomized planning meth\- ods. In addition, RRTs are particularly suited for prob\- lems that involve differential constraints. Basic the\- oretical properties of RRT-based planners are estab\- lished. Several planners based on RRTs are discussed  and compared. Experimental results are presented for  planning problems that involve holonomic constraints  for rigid and articulated bodies, manipulation, nonholonomic constraints, kinodynamic constraints, kinematic  closure constraints, and up to twelve degrees of free\- dom. Key open issues and areas of future research are  also discussed.},
